indegenous policy - see later agenda

4th developemnt in waterloo was not ready for student move-ins. trying to get
some municipal and provincial laws that will prevent housing companies from
leasing to students prior to the development being approved. government 
sponsored document that will be mandated for landlords to present to tennants,
so that tennants know when their rights are being abused. will likely include
language such that if a development isn't ready a tennant isn't bound to 
stay

fall break, talking with societies and engsoc. see email update from andrew
working on a proposal to have a week break, the idea is that this should not
infringe any further into orientation. 

a councillor asked why the template existed if laws still took precedence.  
how does the contract solve move-in issues. outlines scope of the terms
that are allowed to be in a lease agreement to avoid illegal terms. pre-tenancy 
rights are maybe not going to be included in the template, but the hope is that
if there are exact date terms in an agreement there will be wording around
what is allowed. Mainly trying to put it on the governments radar. 

a councillor asked if there was a system to prevent landlords from rejecting 
tennants fi they asked for the government lease. likely bylaw fines if 
landlords were not providing the government lease. 

a councillor asked how students will know about this, given they don't 
know about current laws. Thsi will be largely on students. onus shifts to the
landlords to educate tennants as to why their leases are legal. 

discussing about whether they want to email all first years about hosuing
rghts, and what role feds to educate about housing as opposed to uwaterloo
housing and residence. 

also prodding the region to get more general student education to all student
in the city. 

