Freedom of speech and expression on campus
- Be it resolved that Council adopt the policy on Freedom of Speech and
  Expression on Campus as presented, and
- Be it further resolved that Council task the President to work with the
  University to ensure the University endorses the Chicago Principles by the
  end of April 2018; and
- Be it further resolved that Council task the Executive to work with the
  University to ensure the University does not obligate clubs to hire security
  for their events; and
- Be it further resolved that that Council tasks the Internal Administration
  Committee to amend Club Procedure to ensure that clubs themselves are not
  liable for costs of event security until such time as the University drafts
  policy on this matter.
Alexander, seneca

the policy has been refined wiht the help of PPC, and this version is much
clearer and in line wiht other feds policy. Alexander ran through the terms
of the policy.  

A councillor asked about the equity policy that was mentioned, antonio updated

jason proposed to split the clauses into seperate motions. 
seconded by andrew. 

jason is concerned with the last item, and he thinks that clubs should have
to pay security if there is a cost associated with it. 

The main intent with the grouping is to avoid coupoling policy with current
campus lobbying. 

andrew, jason motioned to group the first three, adn the last item seperate. 

carries unanimously.

Motion now reads
- Be it resolved that Council adopt the policy on Freedom of Speech and
  Expression on Campus as presented, and
- Be it further resolved that Council task the President to work with the
  University to ensure the University endorses the Chicago Principles by the
  end of April 2018; and
- Be it further resolved that Council task the Executive to work with the
  University to ensure the University does not obligate clubs to hire security
  for their events; and

carries unanimously.

The next motion is:
- Be it further resolved that that Council tasks the Internal Administration
  Committee to amend Club Procedure to ensure that clubs themselves are not
  liable for costs of event security until such time as the University drafts
  policy on this matter.
Alexander, seneca

There was some comments that clubs and feds are the same pool of money, so 
either way feds is paying. IAC is empowered to allow clubs to spend money in 
whatever way they want. 

a councillor brought up that it is pretty vague as worded, and that refering
it to a committee is a good way for it to never be seen again.

Andrew moves to postpone the motion till the next meeting
Andrew, Alexander 

carries unanimously. seneca abstained. 

Indigenous Engagement and Inclusivity

for comments

waterloo is about as good as anyone on this issue. waterloo has started to
address indegenous issues, and feds has put together a report to help
inform that discussion. 

a councillor agreed with most of the principles of the policy, but had 
reservationswith the clause at the top of the second page:

BIFRT the Federation of Students shall advocate for the hiring of tenure-track
Indigenous faculty members and professional and administrative staff across
various disciplines;

Was concerned that this made it seem like feds was promoting hiring people
for their ethnicity as opposed to their qualifications. 

The vpe inquired about what specifically was the issue, as teh purpose was
to mainly address parts ot the university community where having someone
with knowledge of indigenous communities.

the president suggested "removing barries" as opposed to advocating for hiring.

a few councillors expressed support for the original wording.

a councillor inquired about operational concerns, and wanted more consultation
with non-indeginious students. 

a councillor re-iterated their support for re-wording the clause on hiring. 

a straw poll was held to inform how the vpe further develops this clause.  

a councillor expressed great support for the major and minor, and provided an
anecdote about the wait list for mohawk language courses.

